Decoding the Enigma: Global Life Expectancy Trends Unveiled (2000-2015)

Life Expectancy

This project aims to analyze global life expectancy trends from 2000 to 2015, recognizing its significance as a measure of a countrys overall health and well-being. By examining various factors such as income, education, healthcare expenditure, disease prevalence, and lifestyle habits, we seek to identify the key drivers behind the improvements in life expectancy observed over the past two decades. The dataset used comprises 2938 observations, providing a rich source of information for assessing changes in life expectancy over time.

Our analysis will explore the relationship between life expectancy and factors like adult and infant mortality, alcohol consumption, healthcare expenditure, and education to determine their impact on lifespan.

We will investigate whether countries with low life expectancy should for example, prioritize increasing healthcare expenditure to improve average lifespan. Additionally, we will examine trends of diseases such as Polio and Measles, as well as the effects of thinness and malnutrition around the world.

The main objective of this article is determining the significance of various predictors on life expectancy and identifying the variables that have the strongest influence on lifespan. Furthermore, we will investigate the relationship between education and lifespan, assessing whether schooling has a positive or negative effect on life expectancy.

The insights gained from this project can inform social and public health systems and guide organizations in implementing changes that promote longer, healthier lives worldwide. The dataset used in this project is publicly available from the World Health Organization (WHO).

Through this comprehensive analysis, we aim to enhance our understanding of the global factors driving life expectancy trends and identify areas for improvement to foster better health outcomes for all.

This analysis will be conducted entirely with the statistical programming language: R.

PLOTS

First and foremost, we want to visualize the average life expectancy range over the 16 year period our dataset covers. We would like to infer if there has been any dramatic, normal or negative change in life expectancy rate around the world.

We see in our plot above that life expectancy rates have steadily gone up around the world. This positive trend indicates significant improvements in global health outcomes over the years. Several factors have contributed to the increase in life expectancy, including advancements in medical technology, improvements in healthcare infrastructure, better access to healthcare services, and increased awareness of healthy lifestyle choices.

The upward trajectory of life expectancy is a testament to the efforts made in disease prevention, early detection, and effective treatment of various illnesses. Immunization programs, better sanitation practices, and improved nutrition have also played a vital role in extending life expectancy and reducing mortality rates.

Moreover, socioeconomic development and progress in education have contributed to better health outcomes. As societies become more prosperous and literate, individuals have greater access to resources and knowledge to make informed decisions about their health.

While the overall trend is positive, it is important to acknowledge that there are still disparities in life expectancy between different regions and populations. Socioeconomic inequalities, access to healthcare, and various social determinants of health continue to influence life expectancy rates in different parts of the world.

Understanding the factors that contribute to the increase in life expectancy globally allows us to develop targeted interventions and policies that can further improve health outcomes and promote longevity. By addressing the underlying determinants of health, we can work towards achieving equitable and sustainable improvements in life expectancy for all individuals worldwide.

Dvelopment Status

In our exploration of life expectancy, we aim to investigate the potential impact of a countrys development status on life expectancy. By employing a boxplot to visualize the data, we can gain valuable insights into the distribution of life expectancy values across the different categories: Developed and Developing.

As we delve deeper into the analysis, several intriguing questions arise. Does being classified as a developed country correlate with higher life expectancy rates? Are developing countries facing unique challenges that influence their life expectancy? Are there notable differences in healthcare systems, socioeconomic factors, or public health initiatives that contribute to varying life expectancy outcomes?

From our chart above, we can see that the bulk of the life expectancy values are distributed around the 75 - 85 years marks for developed countries. For developing countries however, the situation is slightly different with a higher proportion of the data distributed between 60 - 75 years range.

We however have some outliers with some country averaging life expectancy figures below 45 and as low as 36 years. Some of these countries were Haiti in 2010, after the devastating earthquake in Port-au-Prince caused widespread destruction and loss of life. Sierra Leone recorded the next lowest life expectancy rates due to a civil war, which lasted from 1991 to 2002, resulted in widespread violence, displacement, and human rights abuses.

It is also interesting to note that, the bulk of the outliers towards the lower end of the life expectancy scale consisted almost entirely of African countries with Malawi, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Lesotho, Angola, Eritrea, Central African Republic, Swaziland, Uganda, Botswana, Nigeria and Chad averaging some of the lowest figures. It must however be added that these figures were from the early 2000s and some of the main reasons for low life expectancy rates were political instability, civil wars, the prevalence of HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria as well as food insecurity due to droughts leading to malnutrition. To top it all off, was the limited access to healthcare facilities and services which resulted in increased mortality rates and lower life expectancy.

Adult Mortality

WHO defines adult mortality as the rates of both sexes (probability of dying between 15 and 60 years per 1000 population).

According to the plot below, we can see that, between the period of 2000 - 2015, Lesotho had the highest adult mortality rates in the world. Zimbabwe, Botswana, Malawi & Cte dIvoire complete the top five countries with the highest mortality rates. South Africa, Sierra Leone, Zambia, Kenya and South Africa complete the top 10 countries in the world with the highest adult mortality rates in this period.

One common denominator among these top 10 countries as one of the main causes of deaths in adults is HIV/AIDS. This highly contagious and until recently, deadly disease is spread through sexual contact, sharing of needles, through childbirth from mother to child and through breastfeeding, among other ways, caused huge deaths in the late 1990s through the 2000s. The mode of spread took advantage of lack of education which led to stigmatization of the disease, causing infected people to not seek early care until it was too late, it also resulted in ignorance as most people did not know they were also infected until late on. The mechanism of the HIV/AIDS virus is such that, it attacks a victims immune system, rendering it very helpless to fight off other diseases. Add the onset of tuberculosis and other diseases such as malaria and that was a recipe for disaster.

Other major causes such as limited access to health care facilities. Without access to necessary medical care, individuals are more likely to suffer from preventable and treatable illnesses and conditions, such as infections, chronic diseases, and complications during pregnancy and childbirth. Limited access to healthcare can be due to a variety of reasons, including lack of infrastructure, inadequate funding, and insufficient healthcare workers.

Cultural or social barriers can hinder individuals from accessing medical care, limiting their ability to seek or receive necessary treatment. These barriers may arise from deep-rooted beliefs, traditions, or societal norms that discourage seeking medical help. Such obstacles can exacerbate health disparities and impede efforts to improve overall healthcare outcomes.

Infant Deaths

Infant mortality remains a pressing global public health concern, claiming the lives of countless infants each year. This tragic outcome is attributable to a myriad of factors, encompassing limited healthcare access, pervasive poverty, infectious diseases, and the scourge of malnutrition. Despite overall progress in reducing global infant mortality rates over the past few decades, the trajectory has been inconsistent, with certain regions and countries still grappling with alarmingly high infant mortality rates. Consequently, addressing the root causes underlying infant mortality represents a critical challenge for the global healthcare system.

In our plot below, we visualize the top 10 countries worldwide that have borne the highest burden of infant deaths per 1000 live births.

Regrettably, India emerges as the frontrunner in this distressing metric, bearing witness to a staggering toll of over 20,000 infant deaths during the 16-year period examined. Following closely behind, Nigeria, Pakistan, and China claim the unenviable ranks of second, third, and fourth, respectively, while the Democratic Republic of the Congo ranks fifth in this tragic tally.

The situation in India is undeniably tragic, as the number of infant deaths surpasses the very denominator employed to standardize this variable. This heartbreaking reality stems from a complex interplay of factors, including rampant malnutrition, alarmingly low rates of immunization, inadequate access to quality healthcare services, and pervasive poverty.

These pressing challenges extend beyond Indias borders, affecting other countries such as Nigeria and Pakistan that have also experienced infant mortality rates above the average figure during the period under analysis.

Conversely, amidst this distressing landscape, there are countries that have reported a remarkable achievement: no infant deaths per 1000 live births throughout the entire 16-year span of examination.

Alcohol

Alcohol consumption is a complex factor that influences life expectancy, with both positive and negative impacts. While moderate drinking is associated with potential health benefits, excessive alcohol use can give rise to severe health issues, including liver disease, cancer, and cardiovascular disorders, which may ultimately diminish life expectancy.

However, it is crucial to acknowledge that the relationship between alcohol and life expectancy is multifaceted and influenced by various factors. Individual behaviors, socio-economic status, and cultural norms play significant roles in shaping this association. Striking a balance between moderate alcohol consumption and avoiding excessive use is widely recognized as essential for maintaining a healthy and prolonged life expectancy. It is noteworthy that certain cultures and religions, like Islam, strictly prohibit alcohol consumption as part of their core beliefs and practices.

Let us now explore the top 10 countries globally with the highest alcohol consumption rates.

According to our plot, Belarus emerges as the country with the highest per capita consumption of pure alcohol in liters worldwide. The top 10 countries in this regard engage in a fiercely competitive race, with Czechia, Ireland, Lithuania, Croatia, France, Austria, Portugal, Luxembourg, and the UK comprising the rest of the elite group.

Interestingly, an observation worth noting is that the top 20 nations with the highest alcohol consumption are predominantly European, with only the Caribbean nation of Saint Lucia joining the ranks.

It is intriguing to consider the relationship between alcohol consumption and life expectancy within the context of Europes prominence. While Europe dominates the list of countries with the highest average life expectancy, it does not necessarily imply lower life expectancy rates. This observation raises the notion that numerous other factors, including healthcare systems, socio-economic conditions, lifestyle choices, and cultural aspects, significantly influence life expectancy outcomes.

Exploring the interplay between alcohol consumption, societal dynamics, and life expectancy provides valuable insights into the complex nature of public health and underscores the need for comprehensive approaches when analyzing health-related data.

Hepatitis B Immunization Coverage

Hepatitis B, a viral infection that targets the liver, poses a grave threat to individuals worldwide, capable of causing liver damage, liver cancer, and even mortality. Its impact on life expectancy is influenced by various factors, including access to healthcare and vaccination programs. While there has been a decline in the number of Hepatitis B cases in recent decades, it remains a substantial public health challenge, particularly in low- and middle-income countries where vaccination rates are inadequate.

Addressing this global concern necessitates concerted efforts to prevent and control the spread of Hepatitis B. Education campaigns to raise awareness, widespread vaccination programs, and improved accessibility to quality healthcare play pivotal roles in improving public health outcomes. By implementing comprehensive strategies and prioritizing prevention and treatment, we can mitigate the burden of Hepatitis B and safeguard the well-being and longevity of individuals worldwide.

The plot above offers valuable insights into the immunization coverage of 1-year-olds against hepatitis B across different continents. Notably, it reveals that Oceania consistently exhibits the lowest average immunization coverage from 2000 to 2015. Conversely, South America, Europe, and Asia consistently demonstrate the highest coverage rates globally.

Africa initially started with the highest hepatitis B immunization coverage rates among all continents in 2000, boasting nearly 85% coverage. However, there was a steep decline to around 60% before gradually recovering to a decent coverage rate, although consistently lower than the global average.

This plot underscores the significant variation in immunization coverage against hepatitis B among 1-year-olds across continents, with Asia and Africa leading in high coverage, followed by Europe. It emphasizes the critical need for sustained efforts to improve hepatitis B immunization rates worldwide, particularly in Africa and Oceania, to ensure the health and well-being of children while preventing the transmission of this infectious disease.

Hepatitis B immunization among infants has proven remarkably successful in preventing transmission and reducing the global burden of hepatitis B. Routine vaccination programs have contributed to substantial declines in new infections, chronic cases, and associated complications. Early immunization in infancy establishes long-term protection and saves lives. This cost-effective intervention not only safeguards individual health but also contributes to public health by establishing herd immunity.

Hepatitis B immunization plays a pivotal role in global efforts to eliminate viral hepatitis. It effectively prevents vertical transmission from mother to child and interrupts the chain of transmission within communities. The importance of high vaccination coverage lies in its ability to prevent infections, reduce the burden of chronic liver disease, and actively work towards the ambitious goal of global hepatitis elimination.

Ensuring optimal immunization coverage against hepatitis B is crucial in safeguarding infants, communities, and future generations from the devastating impact of this disease. It is a vital component of comprehensive public health strategies aimed at mitigating hepatitis Bs long-term consequences and securing a healthier future for all.

Measles

Measles, an exceptionally contagious viral disease, holds significant implications for public health, particularly in regions with constrained healthcare resources. This infectious ailment can lead to severe complications, including pneumonia, neurological damage, and fatal outcomes. Despite the existence of a highly effective vaccine, measles continues to pose a global threat, with outbreaks emerging in diverse areas.

Mitigating the incidence and impact of measles necessitates addressing the root causes contributing to low vaccination rates and limited healthcare accessibility. Socioeconomic factors, inadequate infrastructure, and challenges in reaching remote communities play crucial roles in hindering vaccination efforts. To combat measles effectively, comprehensive strategies are required, encompassing robust immunization campaigns, health education, and strengthening healthcare systems to ensure equitable access to vaccines and timely medical care.

Furthermore, international collaboration and support are essential in assisting countries with limited resources to enhance their vaccination programs and surveillance systems. By fostering partnerships and sharing best practices, we can work towards achieving measles elimination goals and safeguarding public health on a global scale.

The plot above provides valuable insights into the countries burdened by reported measles cases, namely China, Nigeria, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), India, and Indonesia. Several key factors contribute to this situation, warranting attention and action.

One significant challenge is low vaccination coverage, with certain populations facing obstacles such as limited access to immunization services or vaccine hesitancy driven by various factors. Weak healthcare systems, inadequate infrastructure, and limited resources further compound the problem, hampering the efficient delivery of vaccination programs and surveillance initiatives.

The large population sizes of these countries amplify the scale of reported measles cases, creating additional complexities. Moreover, reaching remote or marginalized communities poses a formidable challenge due to geographical barriers, social disparities, and limited healthcare accessibility, further hindering vaccination efforts.

Effectively addressing these issues requires a multi-faceted approach. Strengthening immunization programs by expanding coverage, ensuring vaccine availability, and improving cold chain logistics is crucial. Enhancing healthcare infrastructure, including expanding healthcare facilities and training healthcare workers, is essential for delivering vaccines and providing comprehensive healthcare services.

Promoting community engagement and awareness through education, communication campaigns, and addressing vaccine hesitancy can help overcome barriers to vaccination. Establishing robust surveillance systems, including case detection, reporting, and response mechanisms, is vital to track and control measles outbreaks effectively.

International collaboration, technical assistance, and financial support play pivotal roles in assisting countries burdened by measles cases. By addressing these contributing factors comprehensively, we can strive towards reducing the burden of measles, increasing immunization coverage, and ultimately protecting the health and well-being of communities in these countries.

Deaths Under 5

Deaths under 5 is a pivotal metric used in public health and demographic studies to evaluate the mortality rates and overall welfare of children below the age of five. It serves as an informative indicator that sheds light on the health and survival of young children within a population.

This term encompasses the number of fatalities that occur during the crucial first five years of life, a period marked by significant physical, cognitive, and emotional development. By examining deaths under 5, researchers and policymakers gain crucial insights into child mortality rates, allowing them to identify regions or communities facing elevated risks and disparities in child survival.

Monitoring deaths under 5 plays a vital role in tracking progress towards global targets, such as the Sustainable Development Goals, which aim to reduce child mortality and improve child well-being. This indicator enables the assessment of healthcare systems effectiveness, including access to essential services like immunization, nutrition, and healthcare facilities. It also helps identify socio-economic factors, such as poverty, education, and infrastructure, that influence child health outcomes and survival.

By analyzing deaths under 5, stakeholders in public health and policy can pinpoint areas in need of targeted interventions and allocate resources effectively. Strategies aimed at reducing child mortality, such as improved maternal and child healthcare, enhanced access to quality healthcare services, and comprehensive early childhood development programs, can be developed and implemented based on this valuable indicator.

Ultimately, by closely monitoring deaths under 5 and implementing evidence-based interventions, we can strive to improve child well-being, reduce child mortality rates, and create a healthier and more prosperous future for the next generation.

India, Nigeria, Pakistan, China, and the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have encountered substantial hurdles in their quest to decrease child mortality rates, especially among children under the age of 5. Several interrelated factors contribute to these high rates, including malnutrition, prevalence of infectious diseases, gaps in immunization coverage, inadequate healthcare infrastructure, and socio-economic disparities.

Child mortality is exacerbated by malnutrition, which weakens the immune system and makes children more susceptible to illnesses and complications. Infectious diseases such as pneumonia, diarrhea, and malaria also play a significant role, as they are major causes of child deaths in these countries. Insufficient access to timely and complete immunization programs contributes to the vulnerability of children, leaving them unprotected against preventable diseases.

Limited healthcare infrastructure, including a shortage of skilled healthcare professionals, hampers the delivery of essential healthcare services, leading to delayed or inadequate treatment. Socioeconomic disparities further widen the gap, as marginalized communities face additional barriers in accessing healthcare and preventive interventions.

To address these challenges, efforts have been made to improve maternal and child healthcare through initiatives such as antenatal care, skilled birth attendance, and postnatal care. Expanding immunization coverage aims to protect children from vaccine-preventable diseases, while nutrition programs work to combat malnutrition and promote healthy growth. Strengthening healthcare systems, including enhancing infrastructure, training healthcare professionals, and ensuring the availability of essential medications and equipment, is vital.

While progress has been made, sustained efforts, collaboration among stakeholders, and increased investments are necessary to further reduce child mortality rates in these countries. This requires a multi-faceted approach, involving governments, international organizations, healthcare providers, and communities working together to address the complex challenges hindering child survival. By prioritizing child health, we can provide these children with a better chance at a healthy and prosperous life.

Fortunately, efforts to enhance child health and reduce avoidable deaths have led to a steady decline in the global mortality rate of children under five years old. This positive trend can be attributed to various factors, including the effective control and prevention of contagious diseases, advancements in maternal and child healthcare, a focus on improving nutrition, the development of healthcare infrastructure, and the implementation of sound policies.

Remarkable progress has been observed in regions such as Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa, where targeted initiatives have successfully tackled the unique challenges faced by these regions. By tailoring interventions to specific contexts, these areas have experienced notable improvements in child survival rates.

Interestingly, when examining deaths under the age of five across continents, Oceania consistently stands out as the region with the lowest number of child deaths. In stark contrast, Asia reported the highest number of child deaths under five in the year 2000, recording a total of 5,027 fatalities. These contrasting figures highlight the significant variations in child mortality rates across different regions.

The progress achieved in reducing child mortality globally serves as a testament to the effectiveness of comprehensive strategies that encompass various aspects of child health. Continued efforts to address the underlying causes of child mortality, promote access to quality healthcare, improve nutrition, and implement evidence-based policies are crucial to further enhance child survival rates and ensure a brighter future for children worldwide.

Polio

Polio, a highly contagious viral disease, poses a significant threat to public health due to its easy transmission through contaminated sources. The virus can spread rapidly within communities, leading to widespread infections. The most severe consequence of polio is paralysis, which can result in lifelong disabilities, affecting mobility and independence, particularly in young children whose immune systems are still developing.

What makes polio even more dangerous is the absence of a cure. While supportive treatments can help manage symptoms and complications, there is no specific medication to eradicate the virus or reverse its effects. This underscores the critical role of vaccination in preventing polio and protecting individuals from its devastating consequences.

It is important to recognize that polios impact extends beyond borders. It can easily spread across countries and continents through travel and population movements, posing a risk of reintroduction even in regions that have successfully eliminated the disease. This emphasizes the ongoing need for comprehensive vaccination programs, surveillance systems, and global collaboration to ensure effective prevention and control of polio.

Significant efforts have been made to eradicate polio worldwide, including vaccination campaigns, robust surveillance, and community engagement. Through these collective endeavors, polio cases have been reduced, and outbreaks have been contained. By achieving global eradication, we can create a safer future where the threat of polio is eliminated, and the well-being of individuals, especially children, is protected from this dangerous disease.

Europe, Africa, and Asia stand out as regions with the highest immunization coverage among 1-year-olds, reflecting the success of proactive government policies and well-functioning healthcare systems, particularly in Europe. Fruitful collaborations between local governments, healthcare providers, and international organizations, along with active public health campaigns, community outreach programs, and educational initiatives, have effectively raised awareness about the importance of vaccination. These efforts have addressed misconceptions and barriers that could hinder immunization, leading to high coverage rates.

Notably, several countries achieved impressive 99% immunization coverage by 2015, including Bolivia, Cuba, Fiji, Jordan, Maldives, Saint Lucia, Turkmenistan, and Albania. Their achievements demonstrate the effectiveness of focused immunization programs and the commitment to ensuring high vaccination rates.

Polio immunization plays a vital role in the global fight against the disease, providing long-lasting protection and preventing its spread. By vaccinating individuals, especially children, we significantly reduce the risk of polio infection and its devastating consequences.

The primary objective of polio immunization is global eradication, a goal that has made remarkable progress in reducing cases and declaring polio-free regions. Beyond individual protection, immunization contributes to community defense through herd immunity, where a high proportion of vaccinated individuals shields those who cannot be vaccinated.

Moreover, polio immunization enhances global health security by preventing the importation of cases. It is a cost-effective intervention that saves lives, reduces the burden on healthcare systems, and improves overall well-being.

The success of polio immunization campaigns offers valuable lessons for addressing other infectious diseases and strengthening healthcare systems and response capacities. It underscores the importance of comprehensive vaccination programs, strong partnerships, and sustained efforts to achieve optimal immunization coverage.

In conclusion, polio immunization is a critical tool in preventing and eradicating the disease. It provides long-lasting protection, contributes to global health security, is cost-effective, and offers insights and strategies for tackling future public health challenges. Prioritizing polio immunization not only saves lives but also creates a healthier world for generations to come.

HIV AIDS

HIV, a viral infection that weakens the immune system, has had a significant impact on life expectancy, leading to substantial challenges in combating the HIV epidemic, which has resulted in a decline in life expectancy over the years.

Although progress has been made in combating the HIV epidemic and improving life expectancy, significant challenges persist. Factors such as the high prevalence of HIV, limited healthcare resources, and social and economic disparities continue to hinder the progress made in the countries most affected by the epidemic. Sustaining the gains achieved and further improving life expectancy requires ongoing efforts to address the underlying factors contributing to the spread of HIV.

To provide a visual representation of the impact of HIV/AIDS on child mortality, the plot below depicts HIV/AIDS-related deaths per 1000 live births among children aged 0 to 4. The animated plot showcases the trends in the countries hit hardest by the epidemic, illustrating the changes in HIV/AIDS-related child mortality rates over time.

This plot serves as a valuable tool for monitoring the effectiveness of interventions and identifying countries where targeted efforts are needed. By analyzing the trends in HIV/AIDS-related child mortality, policymakers, healthcare professionals, and researchers can gain insights into the progress made and areas that require further attention.

Through strategic interventions such as increased access to antiretroviral therapy (ART), prevention programs, and comprehensive healthcare services, it is possible to reduce HIV/AIDS-related child mortality and improve the overall well-being of affected communities. By focusing on the hardest-hit countries and implementing evidence-based strategies, we can continue the journey towards achieving sustainable improvements in life expectancy and ultimately ending the HIV epidemic.

There is correlation between life expectancy and HIV/AIDS related mortalities per 1000 live births, particularly in countries heavily impacted by the HIV epidemic. Swaziland, Zimbabwe, Lesotho, South Africa, Malawi, and Botswana are among the nations with a high prevalence of HIV, resulting in an increased risk of transmitting the virus from mother to child.

Infants born to HIV-positive mothers have a greater chance of acquiring the infection and encountering complications that can lead to higher mortality rates. As a consequence, these countries often exhibit elevated mortality rates per 1000 live births compared to regions with lower HIV prevalence.

Recent efforts have been made to decrease the mortality rate per 1000 live births by preventing mother-to-child transmission of HIV and enhancing access to antiretroviral treatment for pregnant women. These initiatives aim to minimize HIV transmission from mothers to infants, ultimately improving child survival rates and reducing infant mortality associated with HIV.

However, addressing HIV-related deaths among children necessitates a comprehensive approach that involves early detection, suitable treatment, and continuous care and support. Additionally, endeavors to reduce mortality rates per 1000 live births in these countries should not solely concentrate on HIV but also take into account other factors that contribute to infant mortality, such as healthcare accessibility, nutrition, and overall socioeconomic conditions.

In conclusion, the impact of HIV on life expectancy is closely connected to the mortality rate per 1000 live births, particularly in countries significantly affected by the HIV epidemic. Progress has been made in preventing mother-to-child transmission of HIV and improving access to antiretroviral treatment, resulting in a decline in infant mortality rates. However, effectively addressing HIV-related deaths among children requires a comprehensive approach that addresses both HIV-specific factors and broader determinants of child health and well-being.

Schooling

Education positively influences life expectancy by improving health literacy, access to healthcare, and promoting healthier behaviors. It also contributes to socioeconomic development, reducing poverty and improving healthcare access. Educated individuals can advocate for their rights and participate in community development, benefiting public health. Disparities in education can impact health outcomes and life expectancy. Investing in education can significantly improve population health and reduce health inequalities. Education empowers individuals to make informed health decisions and seek timely medical care. It promotes healthier choices, preventing chronic diseases and increasing life expectancy. Education is linked to socioeconomic development, providing better employment opportunities and access to quality healthcare. It enables active participation in community development and advocacy for health-related policies. Equitable access to education is essential for maximizing its impact on health outcomes. By investing in education, governments can create a healthier future for all.

We will investigate trends in schooling years patterns around the globe.

We can see that, for Africa, achieving above-average figures for years of schooling has been a persistent challenge. Several factors have hindered the continents progress, including limited access to education, economic difficulties, cultural and social norms, political instability, and gender disparities. These factors collectively contribute to Africas struggle in attaining higher levels of education.

Insufficient resources and inadequate infrastructure pose significant obstacles to educational advancement. Additionally, competing priorities divert attention and resources away from education. Societal norms and early marriage practices disproportionately affect girls, limiting their access to education. Furthermore, political instability and conflicts disrupt the educational system, further exacerbating the situation.

Addressing these challenges necessitates sustained efforts in various areas. Adequate funding must be allocated to education, enabling improvements in infrastructure and educational resources. Gender disparities must be addressed to ensure equal educational opportunities for girls. Promoting inclusive education that caters to diverse needs and backgrounds is essential. Finally, prioritizing education as a key driver of development and improved life expectancy is crucial.

By focusing on these areas and implementing comprehensive strategies, Africa can make significant progress in overcoming the barriers to education, ultimately leading to improved life expectancy and socioeconomic development across the continent.

By identifying the most influential factors and their interactions, we can prioritize interventions that have the greatest potential to improve life expectancy and overall population health.

We will use empirical evidence and statistical analysis to pave the way to a deeper understanding of the factors shaping life expectancy, ultimately paving the path towards a healthier future for all.

Initial model

We will first build a linear regression model with all the variables in our data to determine alongside the above correlated variables, statistically significant variables that impact life expectancy.

We will then use our model to make predictions and evaluate our model performance using the metrics: Mean Standard Error (MSE) and R-squared (Coefficient of Determination).

Why? The MSE a measure of how well the predictions of a model match the actual values in a given dataset. It looks at the average difference between the predicted values and the actual values. Think of it as a way to measure how close the models predictions are to the real values.

A lower MSE means that the models predictions are closer to the actual values, which is generally better.

Also, R-squared is a measure of how much of the variability in the outcome variable (the thing were trying to predict: life expectancy) can be explained by the models input variables. It tells us how well the model fits the data. R-squared ranges from 0 to 1, where 1 means the model explains all the variation, and 0 means it doesnt explain any.

So, a higher R-squared is generally better because it means the model is doing a good job of explaining the patterns in the data.

We will build our initial model using all variables except the character variables, country, status and continent to get a feel for our data and find out

Issue with Multicollinearity

We used the VIF (Variance Inflation Factor) metric to measure the degree of multicollinearity between each predictor variable and the other variables in the model.

Generally, a VIF value of 1 indicates no multicollinearity, as it implies that the variable is not linearly correlated with the other predictors, whereas a VIF value greater than 1 indicates some level of multicollinearity, with higher values indicating stronger multicollinearity.

For example, a VIF value of 262.190357 for infant_deaths and 256.439025 for deaths_under_5 suggest a very high degree of multicollinearity between these variables and the other predictors. On the other hand, variables like year, adult_mortality, and hepatitis_b for example have relatively low VIF values, close to 1, indicating a minimal degree of multicollinearity with other predictors.

Based on tests conducted, multicollinearity does not affect the model performance so much and some of the variables are too conceptually important to be simply removed from our dataset so we still keep them for our initial model.

The cross-validation results for our above linear regression model are as follows:

  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): the RMSE is 3.69, which indicates that, on average, the predicted values have an error of around 4 years compared to the actual life expectancy values.

  • R-squared: The R-squared value measures the proportion of variance in the target variable (life_expectancy) that can be explained by the predictor variables. The R-squared value of 0.822881 suggests that approximately 82.29% of the variability in life expectancy can be explained by the predictor variables included in the model.

  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error): The MAE represents the average absolute difference between the predicted values and the actual values. In this case, the MAE is 2.831042, indicating that, on average, the predicted values deviate by approximately 2.83 years from the actual values.

Overall, the model shows reasonably good performance in predicting life expectancy based on the selected predictor variables, with a low RMSE, 3.69 years, a high R-squared of 82.29%, which shows that that a larger proportion of the variance in the target variable (life expectancy) is explained by the predictors, and a low MAE deviation of 2.83 years, highlighting our models good predictive performance.

Now that we have a baseline algorithm, we can use a comparison algorithm. For our dataset, Gradient Boosting, Support Vector Machines and Random Forests could all be used but since we want to go deep into our dataset, we will use the Random Forest Algorithm as our comparison model.

Random Forests are usually far more accurate than linear regression models, automatically measures feature importance, captures non-linear relationships that linear regression models fail to do and is less sensitive to outliers and quite resistant to overfitting since it uses bootstrapping, feature randomization and regularization.

We will initially build our model with all variables and narrow down to the important ones just like for the linear regression model.

Our random forest model consisted of 500 decision trees, each making predictions on a subset of randomly selected variables. This ensemble approach allows the model to combine the predictions of multiple trees, resulting in more accurate and robust predictions. The number of variables tried at each split was set to six, ensuring a diverse set of features were considered during the models training process.

The evaluation metrics of the random forest model provide valuable insights into its performance. The mean of squared residuals, which measures the average prediction error, was found to be 3.483175 years. This indicates that, on average, the models predictions deviated from the actual life expectancy values by this amount squared, around 12 years. The lower value of the mean squared residuals suggests better accuracy and precision in the models predictions.

Another important metric is the percentage of variance explained by the model, which was determined to be 95.45%. This indicates that the random forest model captures a significant portion of the variability in the life expectancy data. In other words, it effectively accounts for the factors influencing life expectancy and provides a comprehensive understanding of the relationship between the input variables and the target variable.

To further evaluate the models performance, the mean squared error (MSE) and the R-squared coefficient were calculated. The MSE was found to be 4.169969 years, indicating that the models predictions deviated from the actual values by this amount squared, on average. This lower MSE value suggests better accuracy and a closer fit to the observed data.

The R-squared coefficient, which ranges from 0 to 1, measures the proportion of the variance in the life expectancy that can be explained by the model. In this case, the R-squared value was determined to be 0.9487278. This implies that approximately 94.87% of the variability in life expectancy can be attributed to the input variables included in the model. A higher R-squared value indicates a better fit and suggests that the model captures a substantial portion of the underlying relationships.

In summary, the random forest model demonstrated strong performance in predicting life expectancy. With its ensemble approach and consideration of multiple input variables, the model achieved low prediction errors (MSE), high variance explained, and a high R-squared coefficient. These results provide evidence that the random forest algorithm is well-suited for this task and can effectively capture the complex relationships between the input variables and life expectancy.
